result.execSummary:
The defendant Nikki Paskel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Robbery with Threat of Force [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Nikki Paskel in court with attorney Valeria Lenise Taylor.  Defendant Nikki Paskel in custody.  Benjamin A. Wesson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Matter in court for continuation of Sentencing Hearing.
1 correction made to the PSI.
Sentencing continues. Statements made by the State, defense counsel and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT 2:   
Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 7 YEARS.  
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 4 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 YEARS. 
Credit given for 199 days time served if revoked.

Court finds defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Court finds defendant is eligilble for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

COURT STAYS sentence and places defendant on PROBATION for 4 YEARS under the supervision of the Wisconsin Department of Corrections.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION (AS TO COUNT 2): 
* Comply with the standard rules of probation/extended supervision.
* SERVE 12 MONTHS "condition time".  The first 6 months are to be served as straight time.  As to the remaining 6 months, Court allows release privileges for Day Reporting Center purposes only.  **Court approves the defendant to attend the Day Reporting Center for the following:  Job training programming, counseling, cognitive behavior therapy, and educational programming.
* No contact with the victim, Andrew T.
* No contact with the co-actors.
* Complete a job training program to enhance ability to obtain employment.
* Obtain a GED or HSED.
* Cooperate and participate with a mental health evaluation and follow any recommended treatment.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* Provide a DNA sample and PAY DNA surcharge - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Conditions of extended supervision are the same as the conditions of probation.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Appeal rights given.

Parties have now reached an agreement.

Upon State's motion and pursuant to negotiations, Court ordered Count #2 AMENDED to Robbery with Threat of Force as a Party to a Crime, contrary to Wisc. Stats. Sec. 943.32(1)(b), 939.05.
NO AMENDED INFORMATION FILED.

AS TO COUNT 2 (AMENDED):    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms or body armor. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
